Components and system versions used in this article:
- *OS*: Ubuntu 18.04 LTS
- *MySQL*: 5.7.22
- *gcc*: 7.3.0
- *g++*: 7.3.0
- *Python*: 3.6.5

First, install various dependencies:

```bash
sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get install libssl-dev mysql-server libmysqld-dev mysql-client libmysqlclient-dev gcc g++ python3
```

= Compiling the Engine

Next, download the engine source code from the #link("https://github.com/kbengine/kbengine")[official repository]. I downloaded version 1.1.8, which was the latest at that time:

```bash
wget https://github.com/kbengine/kbengine/archive/v1.1.8.tar.gz
tar -xzvf v1.1.8.tar.gz
```

Then you can compile the code:

```bash
cd kbengine-1.1.8/kbe/src
chmod -R 755 .
make
```

I encountered the following error during compilation:

```bash
/usr/lib/gcc/x86_64-linux-gnu/7/include/mm_malloc.h:34:16: error: declaration of 'int posix_memalign(void**, size_t, size_t) throw ()' has a different exception specifier
... (long error output)
```

If you encounter this error, please refer to this #link("https://gist.github.com/johnmurrayvi/5879822")[Gist].

If the compilation ends without any errors, it means the compilation was successful, and next are some additional configurations before running the server.

= Environment Variables

Modify the corresponding configuration file based on your shell; here I use the default bash:

```bash
vim ~/.bashrc
```

Copy the following content to the bottom of the file:

```bash
ulimit -c unlimited
export KBE_ROOT=path_to_engine_directory
export KBE_RES_PATH=$KBE_ROOT/kbe/res/:$KBE_ROOT/assets/:$KBE_ROOT/assets/scripts/:$KBE_ROOT/assets/res/
export KBE_BIN_PATH=$KBE_ROOT/kbe/bin/server/
```

Save and exit, then make it effective:

```bash
source ~/.bashrc
```

= Database Configuration

First, create the required database:

```
mysql> create database kbe;
```

Create the required user:

```
mysql> grant all privileges on *.* to kbe@'%' identified by 'pwd123456';
```

After completing this, exit MySQL and log in again with the created user:

```bash
mysql -u kbe -p
```

Enter the password, and if you can access MySQL, it means the creation was successful.

The database name and username/password created above are the default values for the engine. If you used different names according to your preferences, you will need to modify the corresponding settings in the engine configuration file:

```bash
vim <engine_root_directory>/kbe/res/server/kbengine_defaults.xml
```

Find the following section in the file:

```xml
<dbmgr>
        <databaseInterfaces>
            <default>
                <port> 3306 </port>
                <auth>
                    <username> kbe </username>
                    <password> kbe </password>
                    <encrypt> false </encrypt>
                </auth>
                <databaseName> kbe </databaseName>
            </default>
        </databaseInterfaces>
    </dbmgr>
```

You can modify the corresponding fields as needed.

= Running and Stopping

Next, we can run the server:

```bash
# Environment variables are set
sh <engine_root_directory>/assets/start_server.sh
# Environment variables are not set
cd <engine_root_directory>/assets
sh start_server.sh
```

After a successful start, there will be 9 processes. Use the following command to check if it started successfully:

```bash
ps -aux | grep <engine_root_directory>
```

Use the following command to stop the server:

```bash
sh kill_server.sh
```

Or:

```bash
sh safe_kill.sh
```

`Note:` When using _safe_kill.sh_, you need to run the py script with the `python` command. If only python3 is installed, you cannot enter with the _python_ command, so we create a soft link for python3:

```bash
sudo ln -s /usr/bin/python3.6 /usr/bin/python
```

And that's it!

